arch:property.oc:show_val: Excavated 3.90 m north south-by-3.44 m east west.
Major destruction level marked by collapse and the accumulation of fill and debris. Partial collapse of the Propylaeum Retaining Wall.
Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c. Possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512.
Phase XII: Robbing and abandonment continue.
First major construction phase. Floor underlying the Portico Wall of the Propylaeum is built and a sandy fill is deposited.

All the major architectural features of the room, including Loci 2 and 3 the piers of Room 3 Doorway #3, the north south walls of Locus 8 on the west and Locus 4 on the east, as well as the small entry piers standing between the south balk.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of the south gallery cryptoporticus of the Propylaeum West. The temple north colonnade falls from south to north across the Propylaeum, damage is incurred on the Propylaeum Retaining Wall and the entire area is overburdened with soil and debris.

Phase II: First period of major Nabataean construction at the Great Temple complex in the 1st c. BCE. Portico Wall of the Propylaeum built. Construction of the lowest eight steps leading up from the then sand and gravel path to a landing, which may have been the site of an early altar.
The earth and debris collapse of Trench 95 and the debris and collapse of Trench 82 2001.

Coarse rubble fill of sandstone blocks and cobblestones highly contaminated with the dramatic collapse and debris from earthquake action. In areas it tends to be compacted; it is a Munsell Reddish Brown 5YR 4/3 soil. One meter to the west of the Locus 4 wall and at approximately 0.25 m above the floor at an elevation of 891.178 m, a deposit of canalization tiles were found in profusion. All were encrusted with hydraulic cement. They may have collapsed from the roof, because there is no indication from the balk that any sort of canalization system existed within the confines of the trench. It also should be noted that above the floor charcoal flecks were found (Seq. No. 96152) as well as several fragments of glass slag (Seq. No. 96139). Both samples were collected for further analysis.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th through 5th c.
